            <a name='Amie'></a>
            <h2>Amie Gravel </h2>
            <p>Amie is now living in Victoria, and has been a multi-prop spinner for almost 4 years. Her specialties are fire fans, mini hoops and clubs. Amie focuses on flow and dynamic movement. 
            <ul>
               <li>Fan Movement: An intro workshop covering planes, grips, transitions and moving the fans around your body. Don't have fans? Don't worry! Cardboard fan facsimiles will be provided for up to 15 participants to keep.</li>
               <li>Partner Fusion Blues: All levels welcome. Learn the basics of partner blues dance. Explore connection with a partner and dance communication. </li>
            </ul>

            <a name='Iain'></a>
            <h2>Iain Culp</h2>
            <p>I have been practicing the flow arts for about 6 years. I picked up Poi in 2008, joined Spark! Circus on the Thai-Burmese border in 2010, met PsycuSix.Ψ and the Malay flow community in 2011, went to my first festivals in the U.S.A. and Korea in 2012, and taught classes for the first time at Philippine Flow Fest and Singapore's Bornfire Festival in 2013. I've moved back to the United States but am still eager to teach and share. Photos and Videos can be found linked at: facebook.com/light.en.ed
            <ul>
               <li>Man, that's long (string):A beginner to intermediate class about long-string levi-stick, ways to hold it, tech to be done with it, and tricks to make it easier to wrap and unwrap with the string. Because this is a long-string levi-stick class students should already have a wand (if short we will have extra string) and for space each student may need about a 3 meter radius.</li>
               <li>To Dance or not to dance: Movement with your prop: Standing complacently and still is boring. Jumping, spinning, and running around can be overwhelming. Help find a balance between these two states, add skill with your prop, and you've just come up with a winning act. This class focuses on body moment and filling the space while performing using awareness techniques adapted from Chinese KungFu and theatrical performance.</li>
            </ul>

            <a name='Matt'></a>
            <h2>Matt Cantrell </h2>
            <p>Matt began trying to make a circle with a rope and jump through it about 1983 after reading a short article on rope spinning in Hoovey Burges’ Circus Techniques. He quickly learned that although roping was once a popular American hobby it was quickly becoming a lost art. He had to learn a lot by experimentation, trial and error. But he did get some help from a couple great ropers who he met at different times: Vince Bruce and Forrest Hobbs. There seems to be a revival of interest in roping recently and he's excited to be able to share some of what he knows at the Victoria Juggling festival!
            <ul>
               <li>Lasso Workshop:This workshop is for beginners or those that already can spin a rope and want to learn some more tricks. I will show what kind of rope to use, how to make your own lariats from bulk rope, how to take care of your ropes. Beginners will learn how to start a flat loop spinning and some basic tricks as well as some fundamental skills for learning more advanced tricks. Folks who have already spent time tying themselves up in knots will get some pointers on learning to step into/out of a loop, handshaking, juggles, butterfly, Texas skip, ocean wave.</li>
            </ul>

            <a name='Randy'></a>
            <h2>Randy Schless </h2>
            <p>Portland's Randy Lee Schless forgot everything when he was squeezed through his mother's womb, but has and will again understand the secrets of the universe. His method for remembering involves playing with the patterns of objects in space, especially how lines make circles. Check out his website! www.circolution.com  randy lee schless has been drawing shapes in the air for about seven years.  His focus has mostly been contact staff, double staff and multiball palmspinning, but he has lately found a love for poi, and thru years of practice and instruction has developed a somewhat deep understanding of the underlying matrix of object manipulation in general. He is building the Flow Factory in Portland, OR. www.theflowfactorynw.com
            <ul>
               <li>Beginner Doubles Movement: This workshop will serve as a primer for object manipulation methods, techniques and terms.  Prop agnostic. Probably half the class will consist of single prop movement techniques, the other half will deal with the dynamic relationship between two props.</li>
               <li>Partner Acro for Object Manipulators:  This class teaches partner acrobatic tricks that leave one or both of the participants with their hands free and ready to spin something. We will cover counterbalances, stacking and L-basing. Come climb on your friends!</li>
            </ul>

            <a name='Shayne'></a>
            <h2>Shayne King </h2>
            <p>Shayne King (The King of Magic), Former manager of Murray’s Trick and Joke Shop and full time professional magician, started his career performing in the bars and nightclubs of northern British Columbia. He is a 3 time international magic competition gold medal winner. His ability to customize a “magic trick” for any demographic has made his magic show very popular with businesses, service clubs and families all over the lower mainland and Vancouver Island. 
            <ul>
               <li>Magic for Roving Entertainers Shayne will be teaching you: 1. His opening trick that grabs their attention and makes them laugh.(easily made props) 2. A simple card trick with amazing results.(playing cards will be supplied) 3. A rope trick that you can customize for any audience you happen to be performing for.(limited amount of props will be supplied by Shayne but also, easily made) 4. A newspaper trick for all ages which will leave them quite surprised. (printed instruction sheet provided)</li>
            </ul>

            <a name='Ariel'></a>
            <h2>Ariel Amara </h2>
            <p>A performer and dabbler in the arts since a young age, Ariel is an explorer of all things expressive. She has been performing, sharing her joy and passion since 2002 when she discovered the hoop - her launching pad into the realm of circus fun. Inspired to expand from prop based performance, Ariel began clown training in 2010 where she completing three courses through to 2012. She also began experimenting with burlesque and stilt dancing/acrobatics over that time. Ariel specializes in the hoop arts, stilt antics, fire arts, character, costume creation and playshop facilitation. Ariel loves being involved in community arts and has worked with Stillmoon Arts Society as a performer and mentor for over 9 Years and she has facilitated at events such as Hoop Convergence, Madskillz and Pacific Fire. In 2011 and 2012, she joined Spark Circus which travels through Thailand and Burma sharing silly circus bliss with disadvantaged children. Ariel is excited about a shared and ongoing obsession with prop manipulation, super human ridiculousness and continuing to connect with community at home and around the globe. Her primary goals in life are to delight peoples senses and inspire a twinkle in the eye ~ enticing childlike joy, mischief and more... <p>www.inspiredcircus.com
            <ul>
               <li>Odd and All - Hooping for the Adventurous<p>Time to experiment and play! Expanding beyond traditional hooping on the hands and body, we will play with hooping on odd parts of the body, hands free, dynamic transitions, strange tosses, fancy feet and other fun explorations. :D</li>
               <li>Laughter Yoga Clown Jam: Release tension and open your clown chakra. Seriously.<p>Inspire smiles, get sillier, make some friends and wear your clown nose to the side 'cause its cool like that. Laughter to release endorphins and games to stretch your brain. Bring water to drink and something ridiculous to wear if you like. Everyone welcome.</li>
            </ul>

            <a name='Cora'></a>
            <h2>Cora Schiller~Shasta Hoop Fitness</h2>
            <p>I am a completely over the moon into HOOPING<p> I love everything about it from the challenging on &amp; off body techniques, to lil nuances with the variety of hand transitions &amp; surface switches to blindfolded meditation in Bali for long periods of time which led to an awakening in my own practise.<p>I presently teach Hoop Cardio- technique weekly classes &amp; am <p>excited to be offering both Beginner &amp; Intermediate Workshops in the NEW YEAR  !!  I find it fascinating that i tend to be a very fast in most aspects of my being &amp; with hooping i happily hoop slowly. <p>I have seen the hoop transform everyone  !!! HOOP JOY
            <ul>
               <li>Breaks and Paddles- Hoop~ All Levels-  Beginner waist breaks <p>to chest n shoulder breaks n paddles &amp; a few other lil transitional cool surface switches &amp; ideas   (:</li>
               <li>Hoop Skillshare: ALL LEVELS are Welcome  !!<p>  ~ each person shares a technique<p> - that they are presently working on<p>  - are being challenged with,<p>   -or perhaps just mastered. <p>          We give feedback &amp; support each other<p>                with their level of skill <p>        continuing to Spread the Hoop Joy  (:</li>
